      <did>
         <head>Descriptive Summary</head>
         <repository>Special Collections, James Madison
         University</repository>
         <unittitle>The James Madison Memorabilia 
         <unitdate type="inclusive" label="Date">
         1796-1951</unitdate></unittitle>
         <unitid label="Collection number">2099</unitid>
         <physdesc label="Physical Characteristics">This collection
         comprises one Hollinger and one Flat box, and contains
         miscellaneous items.</physdesc>
         <langmaterial label="Language">
            <language langcode="eng">English</language>
         </langmaterial>
      </did>
      <descgrp type="admininfo">
         <head>Administrative Information 
         </head>
         <accessrestrict>
            <head>Access</head>
            <p>There are no restrictions.</p>
         </accessrestrict>
         <userestrict>
            <head>Use Restrictions</head>
            <p>There are no restrictions.</p>
         </userestrict>
         <prefercite>
            <head>Preferred Citation</head>
            <p>The James Madison Memorabilia, Collection #2099, Special
            Collections, Carrier Library, James Madison University,
            Harrisonburg, Va.</p>
         </prefercite>
         <acqinfo>
            <head>Acquisition Information</head>
            <p>All items were present in the metal screened area in the
            stacks called the Cage in September 1982, when the Special
            Collections program was initiated and Room 205 was
            designated for Special Collections. An undated, unsigned
            typescript inventory, referred to below as the original
            inventory, was also present. However, some items listed on
            the inventory were not present when the inventory was
            checked in Nov. 1982. The original inventory, and/or
            written materials accompanying the items, give provenance
            for some but not for all items. In early 1983 the Special
            Collections Librarian created an information sheet for each
            item and boxed the items as a collection. In 1994 the same
            Special Collections Librarian revised the organization of
            the collection and re-boxed it to be consistent with the
            standards developed for manuscript collections. The
            original inventory, the written materials that accompanied
            some items, and the information sheets created in 1983 (on
            which preservation history is noted) are filed in the
            control file in the Special Collections office.</p>
         </acqinfo>
      </descgrp>
      <scopecontent>
         <head>Scope and Content Information</head>
         <p>This collection comprises one Hollinger and one Flat box,
         1796-1951, and contains miscellaneous items alleged to be
         related to James Madison. None of Madison's papers are
         included.</p>
      </scopecontent>
